  "prompt": "Can you be allergic to meat and fish?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to be allergic to meat and fish. Here's a breakdown of these allergies:\n\n### Meat Allergy\n\n- **Alpha-gal Syndrome**: This is a type of meat allergy that develops after a person is bitten by a lone star tick. It can cause an allergic reaction to red meat such as beef, pork, and lamb. Symptoms usually appear 2-6 hours after eating meat and can include hives, itching, digestive issues, and in severe cases, anaphylaxis.\n\n- **Other Meat Allergies**: Less common, but some individuals may have allergies to specific meats like chicken or turkey. These allergies can be due to proteins in the meat or other components like gelatin.\n\n### Fish Allergy\n\n- **Fish Allergy**: This is more common than meat allergies and involves an immune response to proteins found in fish. Common symptoms include hives, swelling, digestive problems, and in severe cases, anaphylaxis. Fish allergies can be triggered by various types of fish, including but not limited to cod, salmon, and tuna.\n\n- **Cross-Reactivity**: People allergic to one type of fish may also react to other types due to similar proteins. However, some individuals can tolerate certain fish species while being allergic to others.\n\n### Diagnosis and Management\n\n- **Diagnosis**: Allergies to meat and fish are typically diagnosed through skin prick tests, blood tests measuring specific IgE antibodies, and sometimes oral food challenges under medical supervision.\n\n- **Management**: The primary treatment is avoidance of the allergenic food. In cases of accidental exposure, antihistamines can help manage mild symptoms, while epinephrine (e.g., an EpiPen) may be necessary for severe reactions.\n\nIf you suspect you have an allergy to meat or fish, it's important to consult with an allergist or healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and management.",
